Measure the participant’s head circumference and choose the cap of the correct size. Sizes available: small (46-52), medium (52-58), large (58-64).
Put the cap on the participant, making sure the Cz electrode position is centered/halfway between the Nasion and Inion.
Make sure the cap is left-right symmetric and then close the chin strap.
The cap is fitted on the participant correctly when Fp1/Fp2 - O1/O2 - T7/T8, viewed from the side, are all in the same plane (with Fp1/Fp2 close to the eyebrows).
ush aside the hair in the electrode opening until the skin is clearly visible.
Apply electrode gel through each electrode opening, using a syringe and a blunt needle.
Make sure the adjacent electrodes do not bridge together.
Connect the impedance meter to the EEG cap.
Cycle through all your electrodes and make sure the impedance is below 10kOhm.
For electrodes having higher impedances than 10kOhm, scrape the skin
by gently twirling a cotton bud.
Attach HPI coils on the forehead and behind the ears (on top of the EEG cap) as shown in Figure 2.
The coils must be covered by the MEG helmet/sensor array, so place them as high on the head as possible.
Tape the yellow coil to the participant. This one will not be used or digitized.
Figure 2. Standard locations of HPI coils.
Make sure the Transmitter is on the chair with the cable pointing down.
Select digitization on the acquisition panel.
Remove the cap of the pen.
Rest the tip of the pen on the nasion and pre-auricular points (see green crosses in Figure 2) and press the button on the pen. Repeat for all fiducial points.
It is recommended to digitize the head frame from left to right to avoid any confusions during the MEG data acquisition.
Make sure the pen is perpendicular to the head.
Stop the digitization after the third point (right pre-auricle) by holding the pen 30cm away from the receivers and clicking once. You should hear two beeps.
heck if the measured location of the pre-auricular points are aligned (x-values must not be more than 5mm displaced).
If necessary, redo measurements by clicking Coordinate frame alignment again and repeat the procedure.
Rest the tip of the pen gently on little hole in the middle of the coils and press the button on the pen. Repeat for all coils.
It is recommended to digitize the HPI coils from left to right to avoid any confusions during the MEG data acquisition.
Stop the digitization after the fourth coil (
) by holding the pen 30cm away from the receivers and clicking once. You should hear two beeps.
heck if the measured location of the HPI coils are aligned (coordinated values must not be more than 5mm displaced).
If necessary, redo measurement by clicking HPI coils again and repeat the procedure.
Rest the tip of the pen gently on the ring around each EEG electrode and press the button on the pen. Repeat for all electrodes, starting from the reference.
EEG electrodes should be digitized in the order provided by the MEG system.
Stop the digitization after the 64th electrodes by holding the pen 30cm away from the receivers and clicking once. You should hear two beeps.
If any EEG electrode is not digitized properly, the procedure can be redone only for that electrode.
Put the pen’s cap back and gently stroke the point of the pen over several (especially bony) shapes of the head: eyebrows, nose, and along the skull, while pressing the button of the pen.
Stop when the head shape is recognizable using the digitized points by holding the pen 30cm away from the receiver and click once. You should hear two beeps.
